text: The trailers that leaked during the Sony hack were A LOT better than the official ones released today. (The UK trailer is slightly better than the US trailer, at least).  The trailers from the hack made the Goosebumps movie look like a modern-day "The Monster Squad". The horrible music choice, and the decision to heavily feature the Hannah love story arc in the trailers indicates that they're trying to reach young girls who may not be interested in, or aware of, Goosebumps, and taking the other audiences for granted. The Sony hack trailers had a good mix of darkness and humor.  This just looks like a manic, "Scooby-Doo"-like mess. I guess Sony wasted too much money cutting 2 trailers for "Pixels" and dumping "Aloha" into theaters to cut a decent, finished trailer for "Goosebumps".

text: I'm not gonna sit here and act like the books or the TV show were a pinnacle of greatness, because they weren't. You read/watch 'em again as an adult and they're unbelievably dumb. But I feel like a Goosebumps movie should try to recapture the way these books felt when we read them as kids - a mix of horror and laughs that stays exciting all the way through, with protagonists you can relate to and monsters that are genuinely creepy.  This just looks...well, unbelievably dumb. And I mean intentionally dumb, like they made this movie to say "Goosebumps? Boy, that was stupid, am I right?" And yeah, it was, but that's not how we remember it.

text: The complaining in the comments baffles me - Goosebumps was never hardcore horror! It was all about kids vs the bizarre and unexplained. The frights came from the monsters, the twists and the tension. The only difference is, it scared you when you were younger. Now, a Goosebumps book wouldn't freak you out as much, if at all. You couldn't put yourself in a child's place coz you have bigger, meaner monsters to face now - tax, mortgages, relationships, insurance, student loans, I could go on... But there'll be kids who watch this, get creeped out by the monsters & go pick up the books out of curiosity. Cue a whole new generation of Goosebumps fans! As for me? I'm excited to see a bunch of beasties from the books that I loved as a kid being brought to big-screen-life in a big monster mash-up. It'll be like a Goosebumps: Greatest Hits :-)

text: To everyone complaining about this, let me clue you in on a few things.  1. Goosebumps is a CHILDREN'S book series. Obviously they're going to gear the film towards kids. If you were expecting the movie to be geared SOLELY to adults who grew up on Goosebumps...you're an idiot. 2. "Why so much comedy?! Goosebumps is supposed to be scary!" First of all, it should have been a clear sign that there would be comedy from the announcement that Jack Black was in this. Second of all, the books are meant to be scary to KIDS. It isn't Fear Street. People are actually expecting Slappy to be along the lines of Chucky? Um, when has Slappy ever actually KILLED anybody? Slappy is a schemer, all he does is play mean pranks to make people think his owners are crazy, so he can blackmail them to be his slaves. Slaves. That's his MO. What then, Slappy? Have them serve you orange juice? The books have ALWAYS had an element of absurdity to them. Living lawn gnomes that like to play pranks and tickle people? An evil sponge that's defeated by kindness? A giant hamster? The books are full of absurdities, that's what makes them fun. This movie's clearly going for that kind of angle. 3. "The show was so much better than this! Where's the Goosebumps theme?!" A) No it wasn't. The show was made on a limited budget, with child actors of varying degrees of acting capability, extremely cheap effects, and often mangled the books they were based on in adaptation. B) You can't know that a low budget children's show is better than a big-budget children's film until you've actually SEEN the film. And C) TAKE OFF YOUR DAMN NOSTALGIA GOGGLES! 4. R.L. Stine is in FULL support of this film, I've seen his twitter feed, he is promoting the hell out of this movie, constantly praising it, and has worked closely with the filmmakers on it. Give it a chance before you dismiss it as garbage.

text: Ok, time for a rant. I only have a few problems with this movie, judging by what I just saw in the trailer.  1: I'm really not liking how they're portraying R.L. Stine in this. At all. From the videos that I've seen of the actual author, he's really humble and not such jack-ass. I wasn't really excited about Jack Black playing him either, but I'm even more upset that it seems like he's being written to act like an ass.  2: the design of the monsters. Some of them look okay and very close to the original book covers. But from what I'm seeing with a lot of them is that they're not even remotely scary. They don't have to look down right terrifying (since this is being made for kids and adults alike) but at the very least, try and make them at least creepy. Even the show looking back at it had some exceptionally creepy and sometimes scary moments. I really wish Slappy had looked more like he did in the books than he does here.

And here's what I like...  1.The praying mantis from Shocker on Shock Street  2.The premise (the idea of something from media/imagination/books/esc is awesome... and it kind of reminds me of Last Action Hero)  3.A lot of the other monsters (though you can't see them for very long) look like actually costumes.  4.It looks like this trailer isn't giving "too much away".

text: I get the arguments here in the comments... some are looking through nostalgia goggles and say it looks too "kiddy".  The others point out the logical argument that that IS the target audience.  Personally I like to look through a lens with a nostalgia tint... I mean, I would have settled for at least a REMIX of the original theme tune, but that's just me.  And yes, it IS for kids, I don't expect Edgar Allan Poe when I look into something Goosebumps related, but my problem is that it looks too... chaotic for Goosebumps.  Like, there are dozens of things going on, we got half a dozen protagonists, about a hundred monsters and Jack freakin' Black as R.L. Stine. My problem isn't that is is "kiddy", because I understand the target audience, and after looking closer I can appreciate the attention given to the Goosebumps universe.  My problem is that it looks like it is just going to give into the assumption that the attention span of children is about half a second.  Kids today don't have as short attention spans as most people in Hollywood would think, but this looks really REALLY chaotic.  I can appreciate some things presented, and I understand it is not intended for me- I and many other people my age are simply here because we had fond memories of what we grew up with.  The original intent of Goosebumps was to get our young selves interested in reading, and if this film manages to rekindle an interest in the franchise for kids of today, then maybe we can get them to pick up a book and become interested. And really, if it does that I will be happy.

First off, that is brilliant fan-service, and secondly, that is truly the core of every Goosebumps book ever written. text: It's sad, but I think this movie is going to be really bad. As an adult, the Goosebumps books may not frighten us; however, the tone of the books was serious, as the characters we're in peril from something they didn't understand. Where as, judging entirely by the trailer, this movie is extremely lighthearted in tone, and it seems is is meant to generate more laughs than scares, which is opposite of the Goosebumps formula. It seems to be parodying the Goosebumps mythos instead of adapting one good story to screen. And because it is a parody, it could be setting itself up for failure like Starsky & Hutch, Green Hornet, and Avatar: The Last Air Bender (which I'm counting as a parody, cause that's the only way that movie makes sense). This movie will generate some slight sales from families of young children going to see it, and of course the nostalgia factor, but over all this movie could flop hard.

text: I was never scared of Goosebumps as a child. Yeah it had me on the edge of my seat and I just HAD to know what was going to happen next, but it never scared me Other things scared me. I got a serious kick out of the things that happened to the characters in the books. I would spend hours upon hours reading Goosebumps each weekend. My favorite series of Goosebumps were the ones where you were in control over what happened in the book "If you want xxx to happen to to page xxx or if you want xxx to happen turn to page xxx" we need more books like that for kids. For people getting upset that this movie does not look "terrifying" then I am sorry that you got so scared from reading Goosebumps as a child, maybe you needed something a little more tame like "The Box Car Kids." I honestly, at 31 years old, can not wait to see this movie. I am so excited to watch it!

author: Christopher Alessandro

text: I get why the filmmakers decided to target a younger demographic for this film, but artistically I think they did it the wrong way.  RL Stine's books, while also targeted at younger demographics, did not shy away from how truly bizarre or horrifying his narratives were.  The subject matter in the Goosebumps books were heavy, the characters were truly scared, and lessons were really taught.  This film replaces all that with slapstick comedy, and it really weakens those characters and stories.  A child being stalked by a dummy, or getting lost in a demented theme park, or finding a camera that predicts the grisly future demise of those photographed are the foundations for great horror films that can still be targeted at younger demographics.  Sony Pictures seem to have totally wussed out of a great opportunity to make a children's movie with real substance.

text: the first book I ever read was "Be Careful What You Wish For"  -- thinking that I was some sort of genius, I went to my ESL teacher and bragged that I just read a 126 page book and then proceeded to ask her how old she was when she first read and how many pages the book was.. she said "oh, I don't know.. I was about 9 and the book was about 12 hundred pages" -- I was so embarrassed that i ran back to the school library and picked up a bigger book.. Beast by Donna Jo Napoli-- half way through, I realized that it was a retelling of the beauty and the beast-- I did finish it and I enjoyed it.... I couldn't go to my teacher and say I read a fairy tale... so i picked up The Gemini Contenders by Robert Ludlum.... the librarian, whom I always had bad experiences with and which I hated and was sure hated me along with everyone else in the world... recognized the author and said that it was her favorite author so she took time to get more books by the same author and give them to me free of charge.. in fact, I have her to thank for most of the Robert Ludlum books in my collection and we've grown to be friends.. good friends.. its amazing what a book can do to you and for you..  but I think, if it wasn't for R.L Stine, I might have never become fan of books....  in short, you bet your sweet potatoes i'll see this movie..

text: To all the people complaining about the complainers, this is really why this movie is already looking problematic: the glory of Goosebumps came from the fact that it gave you GOOSEBUMPS. The books/episodes thrived on themes of the bizarre and fantastical, but also on eeriness and nightmare-inducing notions and characters. That was the fun of it. That was Goosebumps. So now, we're getting a cluster-fuck of every Goosebump creation unleashed in a silly facade of CGI-heavy debauchery which will probably include predictable plot twists and character arcs, cringeworthy dialogue, and a good ol' dosage of Hollywood stereotypes/tropes ala the "new to the neighborhood, always gets detention bad boy gaining some form of heroic redemption," and his misfit best friend who helps him and probably finds love along the way (with buck teeth of course!). Oh, and while we're talking about Hollywood, EVERYONE IS WHITE. And while I love me some Jack Black, this trailer suggests a really bad under-utilization of his talents, which is a damn shame because he could probably make a great R.L. Stine, who, by the way, SHOULDN'T BE TRIPPING INTO SHOPPING CARTS.  This is not the Goosebumps we deserve, because it's not the one we asked for.

text: I think I saw the werewolf from 'Werewolf of Fever Swamp', right?! :D That was my favorite of the series as a kid. I won't see this in theaters (maaaaybe the $2 one), just cuz it doesn't look like it'd be worth the crazy ticket price. But the concept is cute and I like the nostalgia factor, the latter of which EVERY adult should see this movie as. Like others have said, the original book series wasn't meant to be pure horror, but more like kiddie thrillers. They freaked us out as kids because we WERE kids, the target demographic. This movie is targeting a new generation of possible fans (they're gonna have to reprint the series) and, in a small way, us. It's a FAMILY film that parents who grew up on Goosebumps can take their kids to see, as a way of sharing in the experience. It'll also give parents a helpful nudge in persuading kids to read.  The movie has potential. I think it'll either be a flop or a "meh, it was alright" film.

text: Goosebumps (along with all of the recent remakes)  wasn't written for kids, it was written for kids in the 90's. Therefore if they make the movie a 2015 kids movie they actually miss their target demographic and the movie will be bound to be a disappointment for both those who originally loved it and to the new watchers who don't get what the big deal is.

text: So... I have watched this trailer a few times now. Um... So, we see a lot of awesome references in this trailer. I was able to name a lot of them. But... So... Yeah... We see the Ferris wheel rolling after the characters... But at no point in this trailer, nor in any images I'm finding anywhere, have I seen a Horrorland Horror. I'm really hoping this is going to be a late reveal, or they don't reveal it in a trailer at all, and save the enjoyment for when we watch the movie... But it better have at least one Horrorland Horror. I say this because, aside from being my personal favorite Goosebumps creation, it is a major fan favorite. So much so that Stine decided to write a sequel, and then a Horrorland-centric series, it has been the subject of two video games, a board game, and a Tiger handheld game. It is a major icon of Goosebumps, and in a movie where they "release all" of R.L. Stine's creations, it needs a Horror. But, I will say, seeing the Ferris wheel gives me a lot of hope for that.

text: Seems like people are leaving a bunch of negative comments on this film. If you were a kid in the 90's I can't imagine you aren't excited for this. It's freaking Goosebumps in a $85 million dollar production! And it's not so scary you can't bring your kids to go see it. All those 10-15 year olds that we're reading those books are now in their 30's and a lot with families. If you are saying this is going to suck because of Jack Black then you just don't like Jack Black. However, the quality of a movie depend far more on one actor. From what I can see in the trailer he does great. The books were aimed at kids so it's not a big surprise the movie wouldn't be a blood-gore-shit-your-pants-terrifying experience. They may have creeped us all out as kids but that's because we were kids and got spooked by anything kind of creepy. So if you see it bring a 10 year old and ask him if he thought it was scary when the werewolf was chasing them, or if he got creeped out at the very sight of the living dummy. It was creepy to us as kids. Now it just looks awesome ;)

text: I fully recognize the demography that this movie was designed for, young children age 5-12 most likely, and family entertainment.  You know how parents are these days, ultra protective of their precious lil snowflakes.  This movie will be safe for those youngins so probably parents will be comfortable taking them to see.  If you're upset with this movie and its target audience, you really shouldn't be.  You grew up on Goosebumps, and now the next generation will have something to spark their passion to read those books (maybe).  This is one of the older generations flaws, we believe everything we had when we were little belongs to us.  It doesn't, it belongs to the age group we once were and gets handed down to the next generation.  People need to learn to let this stuff go and move on, and revisit and enjoy it, and maybe get your kids into it.  It's not like there's a shortage of quality entertainment.

text: Jesus christ guys, this is not a remake or adaptation even. It is a completely original story. They are making a comedy movie that is based around this idea of releasing all the monsters. I believe it is a genius idea. For one thing, it is a fantastic example of what these nostalgia movies should be. Don't make a half-assed not as good remake, make an original story that continues it or provides a new angle. It is supposed to both bring in old fans who will enjoy the references and finally seeing these monsters in realistic HD CGI, and kids who have never read Goosebumps and will go see the movie. Of course they aren't making an adult horror film as that only services a niche market of people who firstly read Goosebumps as kids, and secondly, still give a shit. Finally, those complaining about it not seeming scary. In case you haven't watched/read 90s Goosebumps in the past 10 years, it isn't scary to anyone but pre-teens. They are fun stories based on 50s horror and scifi for children. Not only that, but in today's world of gory horror and found footage and demons, yetis, living puppets, deranged botanists, spooky skeletons, giant man-eating bugs, and especially werewolves just aren't going to cut it as believably scary. Imagine people who watch the Gallows, Sinister 2, Insidious Chapter 3, and the Conjuring 2 planning to go see a scary movie about these things.  TL;DR - Goosebumps wouldn't even be scary to today's kids. It isn't a remake, it's a comedy based on the stories of Goosebumps. I will only judge the movie based on reviews, but the trailer made me laugh, I liked the CGI, and the cast looks great so I have high hopes.

text: Even though Jack Black doesn't physically look like Stine (The real R.L. Stine looks sort of like a cross between Rick Moranis and Ben Stein), I think he's a great choice to play Stine in this, in terms of the way the writers are trying to portray him. I've heard the real R.L. Stine will make some kind of appearance in the movie as well. I think that should be a "Sly wink" cameo appearance, like what Stan Lee does in the Marvel movies. In terms of the monsters, it looks like a good assortment from the books. I was glad to see @ 1:51 that Slappy will be appearing in it ('Night of the Living Dummy' was the first Goosebumps book I ever read, and he's considered to be easily one of the most iconic Goosebumps characters; I'd be so pissed if he wasn't featured in the movie). Here's hoping that the scarecrows from 'The Scarecrow Walks at Midnight' and the mud monsters from 'You Can't Scare Me' also make some sort of appearance in the film (The mud monsters were among the only Goosebumps characters that actually kind of scared me as a kid). btw, what Goosebumps book was the clown @ 1:20 from? I don't recall any Goosebumps books with a scary clown character.

text: "You've just released every monster I've ever created!"  Okay, a few questions.  First of all, R.L. Stine has written a TON of stuff.  When he says "every monster," does he mean EVERY monster, or just the monsters from the original Goosebumps line?  Furthermore, not all of the monsters in the Goosebumps books were bad.  Some of them tried to help the protagonist, and in some cases the protagonist turned into a monster at the end, or they were revealed to be monsters the whole time.  Are they included, or do only the villainous monsters get free?  Also, what does this movie define as a "monster"?  Some of the Goosebumps villains are humans with magical powers, like Sarabeth from Monster Blood or El Sidney from Bad Hare Day.  Do they get free, or is it only non-humans?    And is there a limit as to how many monsters per book can escape?  I'm inclined to say "no," since we see an army of lawn gnomes in the trailer.  But this makes things really complicated when you consider that some of the Goosebumps books show us (or at least imply) entire populations of monsters.  "Calling All Creeps" ends with the entire school turning into creeps.  Do all of them get free, or is it just the three or four that started it all?  To make matters worse, "The Blob That Ate Everyone" ends with the reveal that the entire story was written by a couple of blob monsters, which implies that they live in some alternate universe populated by blob monsters.  Does every blob monster in the neighborhood get free, or just the two we see?  And what about accessories or items that turn people INTO monsters?  Will we see the Werewolf Skin or the Haunted Mask lying around somewhere, doing nothing?    I kind of want to see the movie just so I can have all of these questions answered.

text: Mis cómplices, este film es super divertido. Se lo super recomiendo!!!.  Molesto por tener que mudarse de una gran ciudad a un pueblo, el adolescente Zach Cooper (Dylan Minnette) descubre el lado positivo de las cosas cuando conoce a una bella muchacha, Hannah (Odeya Rush), quien vive exactamente puerta de por medio, y además se hace amigo rapidamente de Champ (Ryan Lee). Pero aún las cosas positivas tienen desventajas, y Zach lo descubre cuando se entera que el misterioso padre de Hannah es el mismísimo R.L. Stine (Jack Black), el autor de la serie de best-sellers Goosebumps. A medida que Zach empieza a aprender cosas sobre la extraña familia que vive en la casa de al lado, pronto descubre que Stine esconde un peligroso secreto: las criaturas que  sus historias hicieron famosas son reales, y Stine proteje a sus lectores al mantenerlos encerrados en sus libros. Cuando las creaciones de Stine son liberadas por error de sus manuscritos, la vida de Zach da un vuelco aún más extraño. En una alocada noche de aventuras, dependerá de Zach, Hannah, Champ, y Stine el unirse para volver a meter a todos esos productos de la imaginación de Stine, entre ellos Slappy el muñeco viviente, la chica con la máscara maldita, los gnomos y muchos más, otra vez en los libros, el sitio en el que pertenecen, para poder salvar al pueblo.   No se lo pierdan, en todos los cines el 16 DE OCTUBRE del 2015 !!  Un abrazo.  AC

text: You know, I've been thinking a lot recently about how this getting a much more positive reception than the upcoming Jem movie. Obviously these are both cash cow opportunities by the studios to exploit our nostalgia. There's no doubt about that. And the plots for both are nothing new: Jem is the standard young, ordinary person dreams of making it big and does but at the possible cost of her friendships and new love interest, until of course she realizes what's more important (three guesses as to what she chooses). Goosebumps is just Jumanji but with monsters.  With Jem though, they don't appear to be doing anything particularly interesting or new with the source material, just retelling the same bland story, and just giving it a cheap Jem paint job. Aside from the costumes and character names, nothing really seems to retain the charm of the show. Literally, you can swap out Jem and put in any other character and it wouldn't change a thing. Also, the apparent lack of the Misfits and Synergy takes away even more of the show's identity. Goosebumps on the other hand not only brings colorful eye candy to the movie, but also major fan appeal by including just about every single monster from the series and making Slappy (the series unofficial mascot) their leader. And the fact that they're taking a meta approach to the material gives it a unique twist. Again, they're actually trying something different with a standard story.  If the reviews are any indication, then Goosebumps might actually be really great.

text: Some of these comments make me laugh when people disagree with negative opinions. "It's a kids movie" No shit, the books and TV show were for kids too. "You're a selfish generation" A great argument. Honestly, the original series were meant to be horror literature for kids, and they watered it down to a comedy. They made a horror series into a comedy. Of course people are pissed, of course people are shaking their heads. Let's imagine for a moment, how would you feel if someone made Deadpool into a smiley, kind, respectful person when he was put into a movie adaptation? You would think negatively of it to, if you were a deadpool fan. Of course, if you didn't know about it, you would be like "oh, okay". Now, another flaw that could also raise red flags. Why do these books in particular have monsters coming out, when the original books in real life were fine to open, and made to read. How do these books work? He writes them then shuts them? Then how did the books come to be? It seems like Hollywood has tried to just cash in again..

text: Season 4 (1998)  No. in series No. in season Title Directed by Villain Original air date   67 1 "How I Got My Shrunken Head, Part 1" Ron Oliver The Hawlings, The Shrunken Head September 14, 1998 Mark Rowe is given a shrunken head from his explorer aunt, only to discover that it has dark powers. Mark then must travel to the Pacific jungle island of Baladora in order to find her.  This episode is based on the novella, "How I Got My Shrunken Head" in the "Goosebumps" series. 68 2 "How I Got My Shrunken Head, Part 2" Ron Oliver The Hawlings, The Shrunken Head September 14, 1998 Mark learns of the jungle magic hidden in his shrunken head while searching for his aunt, and learns that her assistants want the shrunken head too.  This episode is based on the novella, "How I Got My Shrunken Head" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 69 3 "The Ghost Next Door, Part 1" Don McCutcheon The Dark Figure September 28, 1998 Hannah Fairchild suspects a boy named Danny Anderson of being the ghost of a kid that died in a house fire until she learns from a dark figure that she's the ghost.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Ghost Next Door" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 70 4 "The Ghost Next Door, Part 2" Don McCutcheon The Dark Figure September 28, 1998 After learning of her past and the dark figure's plan to kill Danny, Hannah must save him from a fiery fate so her soul can rest in peace.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Ghost Next Door" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 71 5 "Cry of the Cat, Part 1" Ron Oliver Rip the Cat October 31, 1998 Allison, a teen actress for the upcoming movie Cry of the Cat, gets scratched by a strange cat named Rip and begins acting like a feline.  This episode is based on the novella, "Cry of the Cat" in the "Goosebumps Series 2000". 72 6 "Cry of the Cat, Part 2" Ron Oliver Rip the Cat October 31, 1998 After an accident on the set of Cry of the Cat, Allison is put in a hospital where she learns why the cat who turned her into a monster, Rip, won't stay dead and how it affected her friend's mother.  This episode is based on the novella, "Cry of the Cat" in the "Goosebumps Series 2000". 73 7 "Deep Trouble, Part 1" William Fruet Jacob Ritter November 16, 1998 Billy and Sheena Deep are vacationing in the Caribbean, where they stumble upon a plan to turn normal fish into mutants.  This episode is based on the novella, "Deep Trouble II" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 74 8 "Deep Trouble, Part 2" William Fruet Jacob Ritter November 16, 1998 In this series finale, Billy and Sheena try to stop a mad doctor named Jacob Ritter from unleashing the mutant fish onto the world.  This episode is based on the novella, "Deep Trouble II" in the original "Goosebumps" series.
author: Lebowskifan-2002

text: Season 3 (1997–98)  No. in series No. in season Title Directed by Villain Original air date   45 1 "A Shocker on Shock Street" Randy Bradshaw Erin and Marty's Creator September 6, 1997 Erin Wright and her friend Marty are trapped in an amusement park based on a horror movie series.  This episode is based on the novella, "A Shocker on Shock Street" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 46 2 "My Best Friend is Invisible" William Fruet Brent September 8, 1997 Sammy Jacobs visits a house that's supposedly haunted by the ghost of a lonely boy named Brent, who ends up following him home and becomes his "invisible" friend.  This episode is based on the novella, "My Best Friend is Invisible" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 47 3 "The House of No Return" William Fruet The Married Couple Ghosts September 13, 1997 Mischievous friends Lori, Nathan, and Robbie convince the new kid in town, Chris Wakely, to join their club, Danger, Inc. The catch is that Chris must spend one hour in an old house, allegedly haunted by the ghosts of a married couple.  This episode is based on the novella, "The House of No Return" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 48 4 "Don't Go To Sleep!" John Bell The Reality Police September 20, 1997 After being told that he can't have the attic as his room, Matt Amsterdam goes to sleep in there and finds himself in a chain of alternate worlds and on the run from a police force bent on nabbing anyone who messes with reality.  This episode is based on the novella, "Don't Go To Sleep!" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 49 5 "Click" John Bell The Remote September 27, 1997 Seth Gold mail-orders a remote control that controls his TV, his VCR, his stereo and his life.  This episode is based on the novella, "Click" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 50 6 "An Old Story" Randy Bradshaw Aunt Dahlia & Company October 4, 1997 While being babysat by their Aunt Dahlia, Tom and John are forced to eat prune cookies, which turn them into old men as part of a plot to get pimped out to two of Aunt Dahlia's widow friends who want husbands.  This episode is based on the novella, "An Old Story" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 51 7 "The Barking Ghost" William Fruet The Ghost Dogs October 11, 1997 Cooper Holmes and his new friend Fergie are tricked into switching bodies with ghostly canines.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Barking Ghost" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 52 8 "One Day at HorrorLand, Part 1" William Fruet The HorrorLand Horrors October 25, 1997 The Morris family get trapped in a theme park called "HorrorLand" run by monsters called Horrors.  This episode is based on the novella, "One Day at HorrorLand" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 53 9 "One Day at HorrorLand, Part 2" William Fruet The HorrorLand Horrors November 1, 1997 The Morrises compete on a game show run by the Horrors of HorrorLand.  This episode is based on the novella, "One Day at HorrorLand" in the original "Goosebumps" series, with a different ending. 54 10 "The Haunted House Game" William Fruet The Old Men November 8, 1997 Two friends play a haunted house-themed board game that comes to life and may cost them theirs.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Haunted House Game" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 55 11 "The Perfect School, Part 1" Ron Oliver C.J. November 15, 1997 Having caused trouble once too often, Brian O'Connor gets sent to an all-boys boarding school where the students are cloned and programmed into being well behaved so they can be sent home to their parents while the real students are locked away in a basement prison.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Perfect School" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 56 12 "The Perfect School, Part 2" Ron Oliver C.J. November 15, 1997 Brian discovers that his best friend is an agent for the faculty and tries to fight back against his clone.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Perfect School" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 57 13 "Werewolf Skin, Part 1" Ron Oliver The Werewolf Skins November 22, 1997 Visiting his aunt and uncle in rural Wolf Creek, budding photographer Alex Blackwell discovers a secret about the werewolves that live in the woods.  This episode is based on the novella, "Werewolf Skin" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 58 14 "Werewolf Skin, Part 2" Ron Oliver The Werewolf Skins November 22, 1997 Alex confronts his aunt and uncle about the werewolf skin they use to turn themselves into actual werewolves.  This episode is based on the novella, "Werewolf Skin" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 59 15 "Awesome Ants" Don McCutcheon The Giant Ants February 7, 1998 A kid buys an ant farm that comes with pellets that turn the ants into giants.  This episode is based on the novella, "Awesome Ants" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 60 16 "Bride of the Living Dummy" Randy Bradshaw Slappy, Mary-Ellen February 14, 1998 Slappy is brought back to life and now plans to marry a little girl's doll who proves to be just as evil as Slappy.  This episode is based on the novella, "Bride of the Living Dummy" in the "Goosebumps Series 2000 ". 61 17 "Strained Peas" Don McCutcheon Grace February 21, 1998 Nicholas discovers his new baby sister Grace is a monster who will do whatever it takes to be an only child.  This episode is based on the novella, "Strained Peas" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 62 18 "Say Cheese and Die...Again!" Ron Oliver The Evil Camera February 28, 1998 Greg Banks tries to prove to his English teacher that the evil camera he found does exist so he doesn't have to flunk his class. When Greg unearths it, he accidentally takes Shari's picture which comes out as a negative, prediction that she'll be so thin, she'll waste away while Shari takes Greg's picture. To get back at him for taking her picture, she takes a picture of her own that predicts that he'll become so fat, he'll explode.  This episode is based on the novella, "Say Cheese and Die...Again!" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 63 19 "Chillogy Part 1: Squeal of Fortune" William Fruet Karl April 25, 1998 A greedy girl gets sucked into a toy town called Karlsville where she cheats the people during a lemonade sale and as punishment she turns into a pig-like humanoid as the town chases her down.  Unlike "More Monster Blood", this is an original episode. 64 20 "Chillogy Part 2: Strike Three...You're Doomed" William Fruet Karl May 2, 1998 A boy gets sucked into Karlsville and gets caught in a twisted baseball game.  Unlike "More Monster Blood", this is an original episode. 65 21 "Chillogy Part 3: Escape from Karlsville" William Fruet Karl May 9, 1998 Matthew and Jessica enter the toy town to prevent Matthew's younger brother Todd from being turned into a plastic figurine as part of a contest prize.  Unlike "More Monster Blood", this is an original episode. 66 22 "Teacher's Pet" Stefan Scaini Mr. Blankenship May 16, 1998 Two kids, who on a field trip in the woods, find out why their new science teacher loves snakes so much.  This episode is based on the novella, "Teacher's Pet" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series.
author: Lebowskifan-2002

text: Season 2 (1996–97)  No. in series No. in season Title Directed by Villain Original air date U.S. viewers (in millions)  20 1 "Be Careful What You Wish For..." René Bonnière Clarissa August 10, 1996  N/A When clumsy Samantha Byrd helps a strange fortune teller find her way home, the woman gives Samantha an amulet that grants wishes-but the wishes end up causing misfortune for everyone around her.  This episode is based on the novella, "Be Careful What You Wish For..." in the original "Goosebumps" series. 21 2 "Attack of the Mutant, Part 1" William Fruet The Masked Mutant September 7, 1996  N/A Skipper Matthews finds out his favorite comic book villain, the Masked Mutant, is real after discovering his lair.  This episode is based on the novella, "Attack of the Mutant" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 22 3 "Attack of the Mutant, Part 2" William Fruet The Masked Mutant September 7, 1996  N/A Skipper Matthews fears he's losing his grip on reality after a visit through the Masked Mutant's lair and discovers that his new best friend isn't who she seems.  This episode is based on the novella, "Attack of the Mutant" in the original "Goosebumps" series, with a different ending. 23 4 "Bad Hare Day" John Bell El Sydney September 14, 1996  N/A Tim Swanson steals the bag of tricks from his favorite magician Amaz-O and finds himself unable to control the magic.  This episode is based on the novella, "Bad Hare Day" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 24 5 "The Headless Ghost" Brian R.R. Hebb The Headless Ghost, Sea Captain, Otto September 21, 1996  N/A Pranksters Duane Comack and Stephanie Alpert find themselves trapped in a seaside house haunted by a headless ghost, a sea captain and a ghost of Otto who died falling through a dumbwaiter.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Headless Ghost" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 25 6 "Go Eat Worms" Steve DiMarco The Worms, Mother Worm September 28, 1996  N/A Todd Barstow uses his test worms to pull pranks on his little sister, Regina. Then, his test worms show up in his bed and in his lunch container. Thinking it was Regina, he goes to the woods on a raining night to search for more worms in order to pull a prank on Regina, but uncovers a cave that is inhabited by a giant worm bent on killing Todd for mistreating her babies.  This episode is based on the novella, "Go Eat Worms!" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 26 7 "You Can't Scare Me!" René Bonnière The Mud Monsters October 5, 1996  N/A Two pranksters' quest to scare fearless Courtney ends with the pranksters' running scared when they encounter mud monsters at a local swamp.  This episode is based on the novella, "You Can't Scare Me!" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 27 8 "Revenge of the Lawn Gnomes" William Fruet The Lawn Gnomes October 12, 1996  N/A Joe's dad buys a pair garden gnomes for a lawn contest, but Joe and his sister Mindy discover that the lawn gnomes are alive and cause destruction at night.  This episode is based on the novella, "Revenge of the Lawn Gnomes" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 28 9 "Ghost Beach" Randy Bradshaw Sam, Louisa October 19, 1996  N/A Two siblings visit relatives who live in a haunted house beside a beach.  This episode is based on the novella, "Ghost Beach" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 29 10 "Attack of the Jack O' Lanterns" William Fruet Shane & Shana, The Pumpkinheads October 26, 1996  N/A When two friends trick-or-treat with their rivals, they come upon two pumpkin-headed creatures who force them to trick-or-treat forever.  This episode is based on the novella, "Attack of the Jack O' Lanterns" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 30 11 "The Haunted Mask II, Part 1" William Fruet The Haunted Mask, Second Mask October 29, 1996 9.2[4] Steve Boswell takes an old man-like mask from the same store that Carly-Beth went to and begins to become an old man. Meanwhile, the original Haunted Mask returns to exact his revenge on its former wearer, Carly-Beth.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Haunted Mask II" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 31 12 "The Haunted Mask II, Part 2" William Fruet The Haunted Mask, Second Mask October 29, 1996 9.2[4] Carly-Beth and her friends try to break the Haunted Mask's spell and save Steve from a second Haunted Mask controlled by the original.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Haunted Mask II" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 32 13 "Let's Get Invisible!" Ron Oliver The Reflections November 2, 1996  N/A Max and Noah find a mirror in the attic that turns its users invisible, but on the other side is a world where evil mirror reflections want to switch with real people.  This episode is based on the novella, "Let's get Invisible!" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 33 14 "The Scarecrow Walks at Midnight" Randy Bradshaw The Scarecrows November 9, 1996  N/A An old couple is haunted by demonic scarecrows brought to life by a farmhand's black magic.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Scarecrow Walks at Midnight" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 34 15 "Monster Blood" Timothy Bond Sarabeth, Monster Blood November 16, 1996  N/A Evan Ross and his friend Andy discover a novelty slime called Monster Blood that devours everything in its path, but makes whatever eats it grow-- uncontrollably!  This episode is based on the novella, "Monster Blood" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 35 16 "More Monster Blood" Timothy Bond Monster Blood November 16, 1996  N/A Evan travels back home, only to find that the Monster Blood he thought was destroyed is aboard the plane.  This is an original episode, yet it is based on the novella, "Monster Blood" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 36 17 "Vampire Breath" Ron Oliver Gwendolyn, Count Nightwing November 26, 1996  N/A Freddy and Cara find a bottle that releases an elderly vampire who lost his fangs.  This episode is based on the novella, "Vampire Breath" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 37 18 "How to Kill a Monster" Ron Oliver The Swamp Monster May 1, 1997  N/A Gretchen and Clark stay at their grandparents' house in the middle of a swamp that has a monster locked in a room.  This episode is based on the novella, "How to Kill a Monster" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 38 19 "Calling All Creeps!" Craig Pryce Wart, Brenda, David June 15, 1997  N/A Ricky Beamer plays a prank on his rival that calls the attention of school bullies named Jared, Wart, David and Brenda, all of which are actually purple reptilian aliens bent on world domination.  This episode is based on the novella, "Calling All Creeps!" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 39 20 "Welcome to the Dead House, Part 1" William Fruet The Zombified Citizens of Darkfalls June 29, 1997 5.6[5] The Benson family moves into a house in a neighborhood where its residents were killed in an accident from a chemical factory.  This episode is based on the novella, "Welcome to the Dead House" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 40 21 "Welcome to the Dead House, Part 2" William Fruet The Zombified Citizens of Darkfalls June 29, 1997 5.6[5] The Bensons fight back against their neighbors, who have become zombies as a result of the chemical accident.  This episode is based on the novella, "Welcome to the Dead House" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 41 22 "Don't Wake Mummy" William Fruet The Mummy July 12, 1997  N/A A family inherits a sarcophagus that holds a cursed, living mummy.  This episode is based on the novella, "Don't Wake Mummy" in the "Tales to Give You Goosebumps" series. 42 23 "The Blob That Ate Everyone" Randy Bradshaw A Typewriter, The Blob July 19, 1997  N/A Zack Beauchamp and his best friend Alex wander into an abandoned antique shop and find a typewriter that Zack uses to type up a story about an oozing blob monster that terrorizes the video store at the mall. When Zack goes to the video store the next day, the blob appears in real life and frightens the customers.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Blob That Ate Everyone" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 43 24 "Night of the Living Dummy III, Part 1" Timothy Bond Slappy July 20, 1997 5.8[6] After being taken to the O'Dells family, who owns a collection of ventriloquist dummies, Slappy is brought back to life and plans to test out Zane, an cousin to Trinia and Daniel O'Dells.  This episode is based on the novella, "Night of the Living Dummy III" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 44 25 "Night of the Living Dummy III, Part 2" Timothy Bond Slappy, Rocky July 20, 1997 5.8[6] Slappy, now with help of another ventriloquist dummy named Rocky, conspire to turn Trinia, Daniel, and Zane O'Dells into wood.  This episode is based on the novella, "Night of the Living Dummy III" in the original "Goosebumps" series.
author: Lebowskifan-2002

text: GOOSEBUMPS EPISODE GUIDE  Season 1 (1995–96)  No. in series No. in season Title Directed by Villain Original air date U.S. viewers (in millions)  1 1 "The Haunted Mask, Part 1" Timothy Bond The Haunted Mask October 27, 1995 14.1[1] Carly-Beth Caldwell buys a Halloween mask from a new store, but doesn't heed the storekeeper's warning of wearing the mask for more than three times, which is when the mask begins to change its wearer's personality.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Haunted Mask" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 2 2 "The Haunted Mask, Part 2" Timothy Bond The Haunted Mask October 27, 1995 14.1[1] Carly-Beth tracks down the mask store salesman for a way to break the spell and remove the Haunted Mask.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Haunted Mask" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 3 3 "The Cuckoo Clock of Doom" John Bell The Cuckoo Clock, Tara November 3, 1995  N/A Michael Webster vandalizes his father's new cuckoo clock by twisting the bird's head backwards so his annoying, bratty, trouble-making sister Tara will get blamed for it. However, the plan falls apart when Michael finds himself reliving his disastrous birthday party – and going backwards in time.  This episode is based on the novella, "The Cuckoo Clock of Doom" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 4 4 "The Girl Who Cried Monster" John Bell Mr. Mortman November 10, 1995  N/A Lucy Dark discovers the monstrous dark side of the town librarian during closing time, but no one else believes her. And what's scarier is that this librarian's been invited to dinner!  This episode is based on the novella, "The Girl Who Cried Monster" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 5 5 "Welcome to Camp Nightmare, Part 1" Ron Oliver The Counselors November 17, 1995  N/A Billy's summer camp trip turns scary when his friends start disappearing and a strange creature begins lurking in the woods at night.  This episode is based on the novella, "Welcome to Camp Nightmare" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 6 6 "Welcome to Camp Nightmare, Part 2" Ron Oliver The Counselors November 24, 1995  N/A Billy plots revenge on the counselors of his scary summer camp when they announce a manhunt out on a female camper.  This episode is based on the novella, "Welcome to Camp Nightmare" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 7 7 "The Phantom of the Auditorium" John Bell Brian December 1, 1995  N/A Brooke Rogers and her friend Zeke Matthews think a phantom is behind the acts of sabotage that are impeding rehearsals for their school's new Phantom of the Opera-inspired play, "The Phantom".  This episode is based on the novella, "The Phantom of the Auditorium" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 8 8 "Piano Lessons Can Be Murder" William Fruet Dr. Shreek, Mr. Toggle December 8, 1995  N/A Jerry Hawkins moves to a new house and takes piano lessons from two men, Mr. Toggle and Dr. Shreek (who are obsessed with stealing the hands of his students) and his piano that he finds in his attic is haunted by the ghost of the weird man's mother after she died.  This episode is based on the novella, "Piano Lessons can be Murder" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 9 9 "Return of the Mummy" John Bell Nila, The Mummy of Prince Khor-Ru December 22, 1995  N/A Gabe and his cousin are trapped in a pyramid belonging to an Egyptian queen disguised as a modern-day tour guide.  This episode is based on the novella, "Return of the Mummy" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 10 10 "Night of the Living Dummy II" Ron Oliver Slappy January 12, 1996  N/A Amy Kramer receives a replacement ventriloquist dummy named Slappy, which she accidentally brings to life.  This episode is based on the novella, "Night of the Living Dummy II" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 11 11 "My Hairiest Adventure" David Warry-Smith Dr. Murkin January 19, 1996  N/A Larry Boyd freaks out when his hands become hairy, presumably as a result of expired tanning lotion, and later finds out that his friends have gone missing and there are more dogs in the neighborhood than usual.  This episode is based on the novella, "My Hairiest Adventure" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 12 12 "Stay Out of the Basement, Part 1" William Fruet Dr. Brewer's Clone January 26, 1996  N/A Margaret and Casey investigate the strange experiments in their botanist father's basement -- and find a man in a closet claiming that he's their "real" father.  This episode is based on the novella, "Stay Out of the Basement" in the original "Goosebumps" series. 13 13 "Stay Out of the Basement, Part 2" William Fruet Dr. Brewer's Clone January 26, 1996  N/A Margaret and Casey discover that the man they called "Dad" could be a half-plant, half-human mutant. Ron Oliver The Evil Camera, Spidey February 9, 1996  N/A Three friends find a camera that predicts and causes misfortune on the subject it photographs.
